### Proposal Details

in short i just want to address https://github.com/woodpecker-ci/woodpecker/issues/6717 properly

=> reliably be able to kill ALL sub-processes spawn by exec.Command()

## Problem

this is currently not possible as Windows has no process groups. The Windows-native equivalent is a
[Job Object](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/procthread/job-objects).

as in the pase a generic arg passthrough (#44005) was declined ... and typed fields per use case accepted (#44011)

## so i propose:

Add one new field to `syscall.SysProcAttr` on Windows:

```go
type SysProcAttr struct {
    // existing fields unchanged
    HideWindow                 bool
    CmdLine                    string
    CreationFlags              uint32
    Token                      Token
    ProcessAttributes          *SecurityAttributes
    ThreadAttributes           *SecurityAttributes
    NoInheritHandles           bool
    AdditionalInheritedHandles []Handle
    ParentProcess              Handle

    // NEW

    // JobObjects is a list of job object handles to assign to the new
    // process at creation time using PROC_THREAD_ATTRIBUTE_JOB_LIST.
    //
    // If non-empty, the new process is associated with these jobs before
    // its initial thread starts running.
    //
    // The caller is responsible for creating and configuring the jobs.
    // For example, callers that want child processes to be terminated when
    // the job is closed should configure JOB_OBJECT_LIMIT_KILL_ON_JOB_CLOSE.
    JobObjects []Handle
}
```

When `JobObject != 0`, `StartProcess` passes it via
`PROC_THREAD_ATTRIBUTE_JOB_LIST` in the `STARTUPINFOEX` attribute list.

With this any child process is a member of the job before any user code runs

NOTE: I am at no meas a windows expert and my finding is inspired by https://github.com/microsoft/hcsshim with the help of claude to surface that mechanism

x/sys/windows includes the following type and constructors:

```go
type TrusteeValue uintptr

func TrusteeValueFromString(str string) TrusteeValue {
        return TrusteeValue(unsafe.Pointer(StringToUTF16Ptr(str)))
}
func TrusteeValueFromSID(sid *SID) TrusteeValue {
        return TrusteeValue(unsafe.Pointer(sid))
}
func TrusteeValueFromObjectsAndSid(objectsAndSid *OBJECTS_AND_SID) TrusteeValue {
        return TrusteeValue(unsafe.Pointer(objectsAndSid))
}
func TrusteeValueFromObjectsAndName(objectsAndName *OBJECTS_AND_NAME) TrusteeValue {
        return TrusteeValue(unsafe.Pointer(objectsAndName))
}
```

The constructors are unsafe if used naively: They take some pointer input, cast it to a `uintptr`, and return that `uintptr`.

Three of the constructors may be (I believe) used safely if the user pins the input before calling it and keeps it pinned across the lifetime of the `TrusteeValue`. `TrusteeValueFromString` is fundamentally unsafe, since it allocates a new `[]uint16` and returns a `uintptr` to it.

We should do some combination of documenting safe usage of these functions, deprecating them, and/or replacing them with safer alternatives.

This was reported to us as a potential vulnerability. Due to the fact that these functions are unsafe by design, obviously so, and have no obvious path to practical exploitation, we are not classifying this as a security track issue.

